g parties; the lack of a coherent strategy for managing spoilers in the peace process; and weak international support. Peacemaking in Rwanda generates critical insights into the limits of our contemporary systems for conflict prevention and management, serving as a sobering argument for reform of the international conflict management system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / African.2bisacsh1 aJones, Bruce D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertLynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078425140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978162637408940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781626374089423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781626374089/original  a978-3-11-078425-1  Lynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK